1 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 5-149.6 of Title 70, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 As used in the School Access For Emergency Response Act:
5 1. "Best practices in interoperable emergency communications"
6 means to identify the interoperable emergency communications needs
7 at a school level, to help target technical assistance, funding, and
8 other support, and to prepare for next-generation communications
9 technologies as exemplified by interoperable communications
10 technologies to enhance and better ensure school safety throughout
11 the State of Oklahoma;
12 2. "Board" may alternately or jointly reference the State Board
13 of Education and the Oklahoma Office of Homeland Security;
14 3. "Crisis management plan" means a plan including tactical
15 strategies and actions for responding to an emergency as set forth
16 by the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) Manual IS-0100.C.
17 The key elements of a crisis management plan shall include, but
18 not necessarily be limited to:
19 a. threat assessment, recurring risk assessment, and
20 proactive identification following said assessments,
21 b. crisis response team structure,
22 c. communication protocols, including implementation,
23 training, as well as maintenance and timely upgrading
24 of interoperable communication systems,
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1417 Page 2

1 d. emergency response procedures,
2 e. resource allocation guidelines, and
3 f. recovery and continuity strategies;
4 4. "Department" may alternately or jointly reference the State
5 Board of Education and the State Office of Homeland Security;
6 5. "Grant program" means the School Access for Emergency
7 Response Grant Program created in Section 3 of this act;
8 6. “Incident Command System” (ICS) means the standardized
9 approach to incident management as set forth by Federal Emergency
10 Management Agency (FEMA) Manual IS-0100.C: An Introduction to the
11 Incident Command System. ICS shall be adopted by grant applicants
12 as a precedent to be considered for funding through this act. The
13 Manual includes:
14 a. unified command structure,
15 b. common terminology,
16 c. modular organization,
17 d. integrated communications via interoperable
18 technology, equipment, and training, and
19 e. comprehensive resource management;
20 7. "Interoperability" means the ability of one or more radio
21 systems to communicate with another radio system in real-time.
22 Interoperability includes the teamwork that occurs over real-time
23 radio broadcast channels between school district safety teams,
24 school-based safety teams, and professional emergency responders;
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1417 Page 3

1 8. “Interoperable communications provider” means the supplier
2 or suppliers of interoperable communications technology, both
3 hardware and software, as well as related training, maintenance, and
4 upgrades of interoperable communications systems;
5 9. "Interoperable technology" means software and hardware that
6 enables two different radio systems and other communications devices
7 to communicate seamlessly in real time via radio broadcast channels
8 regardless of underlying technologies or manufacturers;
9 10. "Memorandum of Understanding" (MOU) means an agreement
10 between two or more parties that is designed and intended to
11 formalize a working relationship. Among other components as
12 identified by the stakeholders, the MOU is designed and intended to
13 outline the identified parties agreement to share private, assigned
14 Federal Communications Commission (FCC) licensed radio frequencies
15 or channels as well as other protocols and technologies needed to
16 achieve two-way radio interoperability as contemplated by NIMS IS-
17 0100.C for schools;
18 11. a. "National Response Framework" (NRF) means the manner
19 in which the United States responds to all types of
20 disasters and emergencies and includes the following
21 key elements:
22 (1) enumerated core capabilities of prevention,
23 protection, mitigation, response, and recovery,
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1417 Page 4

1 (2) a component of the National Strategy for Homeland
2 Security that establishes a comprehensive,
3 national, all-hazards approach to domestic
4 incident response,
5 (3) an explanation of the roles and responsibilities
6 of federal, state, local, tribal governments,
7 private sector, and non-governmental
8 organizations in disaster response, and
9 (4) scalable, flexible, and adaptable coordination
10 structures to align key roles and
11 responsibilities across the nation, including
12 (and specifically for the purposes of this act)
13 for small, medium, and large school districts and
14 associated public safety agencies;
15 b. For the purposes of the School Access for Emergency
16 Response Act, NRF:
17 (1) enumerates the interrelationship between school
18 access for emergency response and the National
19 Incident Management System (NIMS), and
20 (2) outlines the operation of NIMS Incident Command
21 System in relations to school access for
22 emergency response;
23 12. "Public safety answering point" means a facility equipped
24 and staffed to provide emergency telephone service;
