22 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
23 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 5-149.7 of Title 70, unless
24 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1417 Page 6

1 A. There is hereby created in the State Department of Education
2 the School Access for Emergency Response Grant Program to provide
3 grants to schools for needed interoperable communication hardware,
4 software, equipment maintenance, and training to allow for seamless
5 communications between first responder communications systems, new
6 or existing school district communications systems, and new or
7 existing school-based systems.
8 B. Grant recipients may use the money received through the
9 grant program for the following purposes:
10 1. To deliver training programs to teach district safety teams
11 and security personnel as well as appropriate school-based safety
12 teams and other personnel basic procedures for effective
13 communications with first responders in an emergency. The training
14 shall be based upon Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA)
15 Manual IS-0100.C: An Introduction to the Incident Command System.
16 As required by federal law and associated regulations, these derived
17 training elements shall include:
18 a. completion of the entire course, which is usually
19 available online through the Federal Emergency
20 Management Agency (FEMA) Emergency Management
21 Institute (EMI) website,
22 b. an expectation of understanding the basic principles
23 and features of ISC, including its purpose,
24 organization, and the roles and responsibilities of
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1417 Page 7

1 key positions within the structure established by the
2 FEMA Manual,
3 c. familiarization with how ISC is applied in various
4 types of school-based incidents, including planned
5 events, natural disasters, and other types of crisis
6 incidents or emergency situations,
7 d. scenario-based exercises to reinforce learning and
8 ensure comprehension of the material,
9 e. a final exam to assess the participant's understanding
10 of the course material. A passing score, often
11 seventy-five percent (75%) or higher, is necessary to
12 receive a certificate of completion,
13 f. a certification upon successful completion of the
14 course and final exam, which may be necessary for
15 certain federal positions or for compliance with
16 federal emergency management directives, and
17 g. periodic refresher courses or continuing education to
18 maintain certification and stay current with any
19 changes or updates to the system;
20 2. To implement an interoperable technology solution to provide
21 or to upgrade the following:
22 a. a system or technology that can be activated and
23 deactivated by a public safety answering point, a
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1417 Page 8

1 network administrator, and a school over both the
2 radio system and other communications networks,
3 b. radio and other technology bridge ability that is
4 nonradio vendor specific for connecting independent
5 school networks, school district networks, and public
6 safety networks in the region, and
7 c. an interoperable real-time radio broadcast solution
8 that operates over specifically managed radio networks
9 and other proactively identified communications
10 networks; and
11 3. To maintain or improve a school's existing interoperable
12 communication hardware or software or to provide interoperable
13 communication hardware and software to a school that does not yet
14 have it.
15 C. The proposed interoperable communications solution shall not
16 increase or impact public safety system loading in existence at the
17 time of the enactment of this act. School-based and school district
18 interoperable communications systems shall consider coverage,
19 capacity, and related features in regard to any necessary radio
20 system capacity expansions where school loading is determined to
21 potentially have more than a negligible impact on preexisting public
22 safety system loading.
23 D. The State Department of Education shall administer the grant
24 program. Subject to the availability of funds, grants shall be paid
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1417 Page 9

1 out of the "School Access for Emergency Response Revolving Fund"
2 created in Section 6 of this act.
3 E. The State Board of Education, in consultation with the grant
4 selection committee created in subsection F of this section, shall
5 implement the grant program in accordance with this act. The
6 Department shall promulgate rules necessary to implement the
7 requirements of this act. At minimum, such rules shall specify the
8 time frames for applying for grants, the form of the grant program
9 application, and the time frames for distributing grant money.
10 These rules shall require that school districts and schools making
11 application shall adopt the National Incident Management System
12 (NIMS) to train personnel in the Incident Command System (IS-0100.C)
13 and conduct joint exercises involving professional first responders
14 with schools and school districts to better coordinate teamwork and
15 overall response to incidents.
16 F. There is hereby created the grant selection committee to
17 work with the State Board of Education to determine whether a grant
18 applicant satisfies the criteria to receive a grant. The committee
19 shall be composed of seven (7) members appointed as specified in
20 this subsection. The members of the committee shall serve without
21 compensation, but shall be reimbursed for all actual and necessary
22 expenses incurred while engaged in the discharge of official duties
23 pursuant to this act in accordance with the State Travel
24 Reimbursement Act. Members of the committee shall meet as often as
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1417 Page 10

1 deem ed necessary by the Board to accomplish the work of the
2 committee. Members of the committee shall be appointed on or before
3 November 1, 2025, as follows:
4 1. The Governor shall appoint one member;
5 2. The Speaker of the Oklahoma House of Representatives shall
6 appoint one member who represents urban or suburban school
7 districts, and one member who represents the chiefs of police;
8 3. The President Pro Tempore of the Oklahoma State Senate shall
9 appoint one member who represents rural school districts, and one
10 member who represents county sheriffs;
11 4. The Commissioner of Public Safety shall appoint one member;
12 and
13 5. The State Superintendent of Public Instruction shall appoint
14 one member.
15 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
16 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 5-149.8 of Title 70, unless
17 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
18 A. A school is required to have a Memorandum of Understanding,
19 as defined in Section 2 of this act, with its regional public safety
20 answering point and the local law enforcement agency or agencies
21 that serve the school for communications interoperability to be
22 eligible to apply for a grant under this act. To receive a grant, a
23 school must submit an application to the Department in accordance
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1417 Page 11

1 with rules promulgated by the Department. At minimum, the
2 application must include the following information:
3 1. A description of the school's current interoperable
4 communication technology, if any;
5 2. A description of efforts that the school has taken to
6 coordinate emergency communication with law enforcement, 9-1-1
7 system administrators, and other schools; and
8 3. A description of the purpose or purposes for which the
9 school would plan to use the grant money, including, but not limited
10 to, proposed training programs, joint exercise plans, and
11 interoperability technology solutions.
12 B. The grant selection committee created in Section 3 of this
13 act shall review the applications received pursuant to this section.
14 In awarding grants, the grant selection committee shall consider
15 whether the school has a crisis management plan in place with safety
16 team members designated for communications with first responders.
17 C. Subject to the availability of funds, on or before June 30,
18 2026, and on or before June 30 each year thereafter for the duration
19 of the grant program, the Board shall award grants as provided in
20 this act. The Board shall distribute the grant money within thirty
21 (30) days after the grants are awarded.
22 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
23 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 5-149.9 of Title 70, unless
24 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1417 Page 12

1 A. On or before January 15, 2028, and on or before January 15
2 each year thereafter for the duration of the grant program, each
3 school district with schools that received a grant through the grant
4 program provided in this act shall submit a report to the
5 Department. At minimum, the report shall include the following
6 information:
7 1. The number of schools within the district that used grant
8 money to provide training programs to appropriate personnel
9 regarding effective communications with first responders in an
10 emergency;
11 2. The number of schools within the district that used grant
12 money to provide or upgrade its interoperable technology, including
13 interoperable communication hardware or software; and
14 3. The estimated number of enrolled students that benefitted or
15 will benefit from how the grant money was utilized.
16 B. On or before May 30, 2028, and on or before May 30 each year
17 thereafter for the duration of the grant program, the Department
18 shall present a summarized report of the activities of the grant
19 program to the Oklahoma Legislature.
